[2] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Fri 18 Dec 2009
Source: The Sydney Morning Herald [edited]
<http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/townsville-faces-two-dengue-outbreaks-20091218-l1ag.html>


The north Queensland city of Townsville now has 2 separate dengue
fever outbreaks, with the wet season yet to start in earnest.
Queensland Health said it had confirmed 9 locally-acquired dengue
[virus] type 1 cases and 2 type 3 cases, in the suburbs of Garbutt,
Heatley and Wulguru. Results on 4 other cases are expected later on
Friday [18 Dec 2009].

Queensland Health medical officer Dr Steven Donohue said the fact
that there were now 2 separate strains in the city, following the
declaration of a fresh outbreak last month [November 2009], was of
great concern. "We are unaware of the origin of this new dengue
[virus] type 3 outbreak, but significant mosquito breeding sites have
been found by mosquito control officers in Wulguru," Dr Donohue said
in a statement. "This is a bad sign given that we have not even had
significant rains yet, and lots of people travel around over Christmas."

He said scientists would test the virus to compare it with the dengue
[virus] type 3 epidemic strain that occurred early this year [2009].
But he said it was unlikely the strain had persisted through from last season.

People who have had another dengue type previously are at increased
risk of more serious illness with a 2nd dose of the disease. This can
include complications such as DHF, which can lead to death.

Doctors have been put on alert, and disease surveillance and mosquito
control staff will be patrolling over the Christmas break.

The north Queensland dengue epidemic during the last wet season was
the worst in 50 years. More than 1000 people were infected with the
virus during the outbreak, which began in November 2008, including an
elderly woman who died due to complications in March this year [2009].

Dengue mosquitoes breed around homes and in urban areas, and
residents have been asked to get rid of water-holding containers and
wear strong repellent.

[Byline: Paul Osborne]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The 17 Dec 2009 issue of ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Co.)
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/17/2774231.htm> reported
that the number of locally acquired type one dengue fever cases in
Townsville, in north Queensland, has risen to 11. Another case has
been confirmed in the western suburb of Garbutt. Queensland Health
says 5 people are still waiting on test results to see if they have
the disease. The 18 Dec 2009 report by ABC (Australian Broadcasting
Co.) <http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/18/2775860.htm>
indicated that blood banks in Townsville have stopped taking red cell
and platelet donations during the dengue outbreak, with 11 confirmed
cases of the disease in the area.

The concern about the spread of dengue virus infections in Queensland
is justified, given the large area where the mosquito vector _Aedes
aegypti_ is found. _Aedes albopictus_, also a dengue virus vector, is
only found in Torres Strait islands on the northern tip of Queensland
(<http://www.health.qld.gov.au/dengue/dengue_fever/mosquito.asp#dengueAustralia>).

An interactive map of Queensland showing the location of Townsville
can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/australia/queensland/brisbane/brisbane/>. A
