[4] Bolivia
Date: Thu 10 Dec 2009
Source: El Deber Digital [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.eldeberdigital.com/2009/2009-12-10/vernotaahora.php?id=091209185222>


The Minister of Health, Ramiro Tapia, yesterday [9 Dec 2009]
expressed his concern about the increase of dengue cases in the
country, mainly in Pando, where 148 affected people have been
recorded, of a total of 172 reported [dengue cases] in the 2nd half
of the year [2009] in all of the national territory. Minister Tapia
indicated that this is an alarming situation because it is an
important epidemiological outbreak. To face this situation, he said
that cleanup campaigns and fumigation will be strengthened in Cobija
and other municipalities in Pando. We are going to propose to the
Pando Health Services that we carry out a day cleanup and spraying in
Cobija, he added.

According to Tapia, of the total [dengue] cases confirmed from June
2009 to the present, 12 are from Santa Cruz, 8 from La Paz, 3 from
Beni and one from Cochabamba [departments; state or province
equivalents]. In relation to Santa Cruz department, the interim chief
for the dengue departmental Health Services program (SEDES), Virgilio
Prieto, stated that the situation is under control. He said that
since [epidemiological] week 45, that is to say since the 1st week of
November 2009, all the suspected [dengue] cases have yielded negative
laboratory results. Prieto indicated that the prevention campaigns by
district, developed by SEDES and the mayor's office, have given good
results. The proof of this is that between January and December
[2009], the [household _Aedes aegypti_] larval infestation rate has
been reduced from 50 percent to 13 percent. This signifies that at
the beginning of the year [2009], 50 or every 100 houses had mosquito
larvae [present], while currently the vect!
or, in its larval phase, is present in only 13 of every 100 homes, he
explained.

Nonetheless, SEDES thinks that prevention campaigns in the provinces
most affected during the dengue epidemic at the beginning of the year
[2009] must be strengthened. Because of this, 56 lightweight and
heavy fumigation machines were delivered, which will be distributed
to all the provinces in the department. The greatest number of
machines are destined for Cordillera and Obispo Santistevan.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[In 2008 and early 2009, lowland Bolivia, and especially the
Department of Santa Cruz, suffered an intense dengue outbreak that
overloaded the medical facilities in the city. One hopes that
situation will not be repeated in the coming months and that the
early preventive measures being implemented will be effective.

