[5] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Tue 8 Dec 2009
Source: So Noticias [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.sonoticias.com.br/noticias/11/97613/sinop-professores-e-alunos-protestam-na-camara-apos-8-mortes-por-dengue>


Teachers, students and friends of Professor Claudemir Bergamo (Tito),
the 8th fatal victim of dengue in Sinop, protested yesterday night [7
Dec 2009] in the session of the municipal council against the
increasing number of deaths in order to press the city for tougher
measures to be taken in order to contain the infestation of the
mosquito that transmits the disease [virus]. Professor Rosa Eulen dos
Santos showed a poster reading: "Dengue: must someone in your family
die, so that you do something about it?" In an interview with So
Noticias, she said that just mobilization will not minimize the
serious problem in the city. "It is our obligation to take charge and
require those who have conditions [for vector breeding sites] to
change to improve this scenario. I believe that we are taking the 1st
part to require action, and, at the same time, we [need] to act and
take care of our homes, inform our neighbors; [this] is our role,
too. But the authorities have the power at hand. I believe we came to
the correct location, to the city council, to ask them to change this
dire situation," she charged.

Cleaning up land and backyards is essential for the elimination of
the mosquito but not the only measure that should be taken, says
Eulen. "The councilors are talking all the time about clean yards,
clean troughs, while dengue fever is not only that. The disease also
involves fast response [FR] service; we need to know what the FR is
offering, how it is dealing with the situation, thinking that
speaking about dengue is much more than talking about cleaning
yards," she charged. After the charges, some council members went to
the podium and made speeches demanding more action.

The largest outbreaks of the disease are in the central area.
Saturday and Sunday [12, 13 Dec 2009], the committee for fighting
dengue is conducting "fine-toothed comb" [action] to eliminate foci
of outbreaks. Thu 16 Dec 2009, a hearing is scheduled for further
action to be taken. According to the latest update released by
Municipal Health, Sinop has, from January 2009 to date, 2491 cases of
dengue fever, 22 of dengue with complications, 17 cases of DHF, 2 of
[dengue] shock syndrome and 6 confirmed deaths, 4 of DHF and 2 with
shock syndrome and 2 under investigation. Of the 3708 [case] reports,
1037 were discarded.

Professor Tito, as news has just reported, died on Sunday night [6
Dec 2009] of DHF. He was 40 years old and lived in the center of the city.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[Sinop has about 100 000 inhabitants, a mortality rate of 8/100 000;
[that] is very high. The incidence rate is around 1500/100 000,
without comments. Mod.LJS]

