[7] South America
Date: Fri 18 Dec 2009
Source: Yahoo Noticias, Salud [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY]
<http://espanol.news.yahoo.com/s/reuters/091218/n_health/salud_dengue_sudamerica__datos>


With the approach of the austral summer in a year marked by the
climatic phenomenon "El Nino," which will increase rainfall and
changes in the temperatures of the region, specialists fear dengue
virus will hit South America harder.

With changes in habits and education -- although insufficient -- as
the maximum preventive tools, the region faces the challenge of
fighting the expansion of the dengue [virus] mosquito vector, _Aedes
aegypti_, which prefers to live near humans in humid places.

Here are some facts of the disease, which appears to have approached
half a million cases this year [2009] in South America: * In 2009,
the countries of the Southern Cone -- Argentina, Brasil, Chile,
Paraguay and Uruguay -- reported 438 704 cases of dengue to the Pan
American Health Organization (PAHO), according to data at the
beginning of December [2009], placing it well ahead of Central
America, in 2nd place with 206 810 cases.

* The cases of DHF, which is the most serious form of the disease, in
the Andean Region and the Southern Cone in 2009 are around 17 000,
which is almost equal to 70 percent of the total registered in the
American Continent.

* As for the number of deaths from the disease, of a total of 364 in
all the Americas, the Southern Cone and the Andean Region -- composed
of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela -- recorded the
highest rates in 2009, with 47 and 20 percent, respectively.

* Brazil, which according to PAHO has 60 percent of the cases of
dengue in the Americas, was one of the countries most affected by the
epidemic of last summer, followed by Bolivia.

* Concerning the average [mean] number of reported cases between
2000-2007, in the Southern Cone, the number of recorded [cases] in
2008 was an increase of 153 percent, with 585 866 cases.

